-- Crude Options Volatility Falls as Futures Jump 1.1 Percent
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-06-06T21:11:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-06-06/crude-options-volatility-falls-as-futures-jump-1-1-percent.html
Crude oil options volatility fell to
the lowest level in seven days as the underlying futures jumped
1.1 percent.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
July, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 21.6 percent on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange  at 4:47 p.m., versus 22.25 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for July delivery rose $1.02
to settle at $94.76 a barrel on the Nymex, the highest
settlement since May 28.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
September $85 puts, which declined 21 cents to 91 a barrel on
5,287 lots at 3:38 p.m. on the Nymex. July $85 puts were the
second-most active, falling 2 cents to 3 cents on volume of
4,894 contracts.  Puts accounted for 69 percent of electronic trading volume
today. In the prior dayâ€™s trading, puts accounted for 53 percent
of 93,589 contracts.  July $102 calls were the most-active options traded in the
previous session, with 4,857 contracts changing hands. They rose
1 cent to 4 cents a barrel. July $90 puts fell 17 cents to 41
cents a barrel on 4,393 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $105 calls with
39,319 contracts. Next were September $85 puts with 37,165 lots
and July $110 calls with 36,931.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
